      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "After arrest, the Vieques 21 were charged with trespassing on federal property and all “reportedly refused to give their word that they would not return to Vieques.”"
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn1",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[1]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " While the other fifteen arrested “were released on their own recognizance or on non-secured $500 bonds,” the Crucians were required to post a $1,000 cash bail “without any apparent explanation.”"
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn2",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[2]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " Once the money for the Crucians was raised, their lawyer tried to post bail but could not locate the clerk. The Crucians’ lawyer “then went to the clerk’s home, but the clerk refused to accept the bail until an official court mandamus was presented. But even shortly thereafter when [the lawyer] produced the necessary document, he was told that hearing on the bail request had to be conducted and was scheduled for 2 p.m. that afternoon.”"
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn3",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[3]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " The Crucians did not return to St. Croix until Monday—two days after being arrested (Figure 1). The Crucians’ attorney filed a suit against the San Juan magistrate and clerks, citing Crucian rights had been violated. “According to a report on the incident heard on Puerto Rican station Channel 2’s evening newscast, the strange legal proceedings may have been a ‘pressure tactic’ used to persuade Crucians to stay out of the Vieques matter.”"
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn4",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[4]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " Despite these tactics, a spokesman for the Committee to Rescue Vieques assured that more St. Croix residents would be joining the Vieques protests that week. One of the Crucian Crusaders, upon his return, stated that when the judge released them “he imposed an additional condition that they not leave St. Croix until their scheduled appearance in court in San Juan next month” and the group had to report weekly to federal marshals in St. Croix."
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn5",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[5]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " Despite these orders, one of the Crucian Crusaders declared: “I will go back if Vieques needs me.”"
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn6",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[6]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "https://archive.org/download/crucian-crusaders-1979/Crucian%20Crusaders%201979.png",
      "caption": "Figure 1 Crucian Crusaders returning to St. Croix after being arrested in Vieques on May 19, 1979. Photo from The St. Croix Avis issue published on December 31, 1979.",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The trials and sentencing of the Vieques 21 took several months, concluding in November 1979. Wilfredo Vélez, one of the ministers arrested and president of the Committee of the Vieques 21, stated the tribunal rejected the group’s petition to be sentenced together. Despite the arrest happening at the same time and place for everyone, the Vieques 21 were prosecuted individually, a tactic Vélez claimed was expended to exhaust the group."
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn7",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[7]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " Although some of the Vieques 21 chose to not present a defense during their trials as a refusal of culpability and U.S. imperialism, those who did present a defense deployed a range of arguments. Defending arguments included: no signage on the beach that stated it was federal property and, regardless, beaches were public property in P.R.; referencing of United Nations (U.N.) resolutions that questioned the presence of the Navy; and the discriminatory nature of the accusations given police had selectively arrested non-Viequenses."
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://4CB60927-65D8-4400-8736-D733BAF9797A#_ftn8",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[8]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "In the end, eleven of the Vieques 21 served prison sentences"
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://359F3898-0B46-442E-9231-7DF613DBA072#_ftn1",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[9]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " of up to six months and all were transferred to prisons outside of P.R., including prisons in the continental U.S. and St. Croix."
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://359F3898-0B46-442E-9231-7DF613DBA072#_ftn2",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[10]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": " Five of the six St. Croix Crusaders served jail time, and the other was sentenced to one year of probation."
        },
        {
          "type": "link",
          "url": "applewebdata://359F3898-0B46-442E-9231-7DF613DBA072#_ftn3",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "[11]"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
